revision.text:
{{Infobox book <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books --> | name = A Study in Scarlet Women | image = A Study in Scarlet Women.jpg | caption = | author = [[Sherry Thomas]] | cover_artist = | country = United States | language = English | genre = [[Mystery fiction|Mystery]] | published = October, 2016 ([[Berkley Books]]) | media_type = Print | pages = 336 | isbn = 978-0425281406 }}
'''''A Study in Scarlet Women''''' is a [[mystery fiction|mystery]] by [[Sherry Thomas]]. It is the first novel of Thomas' "Lady Sherlock series".<ref>{{cite web|last=Lamb|first=Joyce|title=You might say this interview with historical romance author Sherry Thomas has a bit of a theme: Zombies|url=http://happyeverafter.usatoday.com/2016/10/18/sherry-thomas-interview-a-study-in-scarlet-women/|work=[[USA Today]]|date=October 18, 2016|accessdate=January 24, 2018}}</ref> In the novel, Thomas gender-flipped [[Sherlock Holmes]] into Charlotte Holmes.<ref name="npr">{{cite web|last=Wendell|first=Sarah|title=Charlotte Holmes Is On The Case In 'A Study In Scarlet Women'|url=https://www.npr.org/2016/10/23/498562814/charlotte-holmes-is-on-the-case-in-a-study-in-scarlet-women|date=October 23, 2016|accessdate=January 24, 2018}}</ref> Thomas said
{{quote|"A Sherlock Holmes has the luxury of not thinking about such rules. After all, they don’t interfere in his life...Charlotte Holmes has no choice but to deal with them—and how she deals with them would define the paths of her life."<ref>{{cite web|last=Gandhi|first=Lakshmi|title=These writers are putting a new spin on the legendary Sherlock Holmes|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/asian-america/these-writers-are-putting-new-spin-legendary-sherlock-holmes-n834866|work=[[NBC News]]|date=January 5, 2018|accessdate=January 24, 2018}}</ref>}}
Charlotte creates the fiction of a "Sherlock Holmes, consulting detective" and masquerades as his sister to solve crimes<ref name="vox">{{cite web|last=Grady|first=Constance|title=A Study in Scarlet Women’s gender-swapped Sherlock Holmes story is all premise, no plot|url=https://www.vox.com/culture/2016/12/5/13806216/a-study-in-scarlet-women-sherry-thomas-review|work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]|date=December 5, 2016|accessdate=January 24, 2018}}</ref> within the limited opportunities for women in [[Victorian England]].
==Reception== Sarah Wendell, reviewing the book for [[NPR]], said "You'll probably finish it, and start the first page over again, because it's that good."<ref name="npr"/> Constance Grady for ''[[Vox (website)|Vox]]'' gave it two and a half stars saying "A Study in Scarlet Women has a killer premise, some interesting character work, and a regrettably poorly structured plot."<ref name="vox"/>
''[[Book Riot]]'' listed it as one of their "favorite under-the-radar-books" of the year.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bowen|first=Ashley|title=Our Favorite Under-the-Radar Books Published in 2016|url=https://bookriot.com/2016/12/20/favorite-radar-books-published-2016/|website=Book Riot|date=December 20, 2016|accessdate=January 24, 2018}}</ref> ''[[Kirkus Reviews]]'' called it one of the "Best Mysteries and Thrillers of 2016".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kirkusreviews.com/lists/best-mysteries-and-thrillers-2016/study-scarlet-women/#feature|title=Best Fiction of 2016|website=[[Kirkus Reviews]]|accessdate=January 24, 2018}}</ref>
