{{Infobox ancient site | name = Es Skhul | native_name = | alternate_name =Skhul Cave | image = Skhul Cave.JPG | alt = Skhul Cave | caption = Es-Skhul Cave, [[Mount Carmel]], Israel | image_size = 240 | map_type =Israel | map_alt = Skhul Cave | map_caption = location in Israel | map_size = 240 | relief = yes | coordinates = {{coord|32|40|14.4|N|34|57|58.1|E|display=inline,title}} | location = south of the city of [[Haifa]] | region = [[Israel]] | type = | part_of = | length = | width = | area = | height = | depth = | builder = | material = | built = | abandoned = | epochs = [[Palaeolithic]] | cultures =[[Natufian]] | dependency_of = | occupants = | event = | excavations =1928 | archaeologists = [[Dorothy Garrod]] | condition = | ownership = | management = | public_access = | website = | notes = }}
'''Es-Skhul''' ({{lang-ar|السخول}}, meaning kid, young goat) is a [[prehistoric]] [[cave]] site situated {{convert|20 |km|mi|1|abbr=on}} south of the city of [[Haifa]], [[Israel]], and around {{convert|3 |km|mi|1|abbr=on}} from the [[Mediterranean Sea]]. The site was first excavated by [[Dorothy Garrod]] during summer of 1928. The excavation revealed the first evidence of the late [[Epipaleolithic]] [[Natufian]] culture, characterized by the presence of numerous [[microlith]] stone tools, human burials and ground stone tools. Skhul also represents an area where [[Neanderthal]]s - possibly present in the region from 200,000 to 45,000 years ago - may have lived alongside these humans dating to 100,000 years ago.<ref>Olson, S. <u>Mapping Human History.</u> Houghton Mifflin, New York (2003). p.74-75.</ref> The cave also has Middle [[Palaeolithic]] layers.
The remains found at Es Skhul, together with those found at the [[Wadi el-Mughara Caves]] and [[Mugharet el-Zuttiyeh]] were classified in 1939 by [[Arthur Keith]] and [[:de:Theodore D. McCown|Theodore D. McCown]] as ''Palaeoanthropus palestinensis'', a descendent of ''[[Homo heidelbergensis]]''.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=vHKuxy69Lc8C&pg=PA59&lpg=PA59 The Palaeolithic Origins of Human Burial], [[Paul Pettitt]], 2013, p59</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=Kl8gAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA90#v=onepage&q&f=false Human Adaptation in the Asian Palaeolithic: Hominin Dispersal and Behaviour during the Late Quaternary], Ryan J. Rabett, 2012, p90</ref><ref>[https://archive.org/stream/stoneageofmountc02join#page/18/mode/1up The stone age of Mount Carmel : report of the Joint Expedition of the British School of Archaeology in Jerusalem and the American School of Prehistoric Research, 1929-1934], p18</ref>
==See also== * [[List of fossil sites]] (with link directory) * [[List of hominina fossils|List of hominina (hominid) fossils]] (with images) * [[Nahal Me'arot Nature Reserve]] * [[Qesem Cave]] * [[Skhul and Qafzeh hominids]]
