{{infobox organization |name = Henokiens |image = |size = |abbreviation = |motto = |formation = {{start date and age|1981}} |type = [[Voluntary association]] |headquarters = [[Paris]], [[France]] |budget = |website = [http://www.henokiens.com Henokiens.com] }}
The '''Henokiens''' is an association of companies who have been continuously operating and remain family-owned for 200 years or more, and whose descendants still operate at management level.<ref name="franceinter">{{cite web |url=http://www.franceinter.fr/emission-leco-du-matin-henokiens-les-entreprises-de-pere-en-fils |title=Hénokiens, les entreprises de père en fils |date=12 June 2014 |publisher =[[France Inter]] |access-date=1 July 2015}}.</ref> It derives its name from the [[Bible|biblical]] patriarch [[Enoch (ancestor of Noah)|Enoch]] (''Hénoch'' in [[French language|French]]), who lived for 365 years before he was taken by God instead of dying.<ref>{{cite news |last= Lipovitch |first= Gérard |date= November 2003|title= The Henokiens. Family business history. |newspaper= The Family Business Network|url=http://www.henokiens.com/userfiles/file/press/FBN_Newsletter.pdf}}</ref>
Founded in 1981 by the then-[[chairman]] of [[Marie Brizard et Roger International|Marie Brizard]], the association started with 4 French members<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.beretta.com/en-us/world-of-beretta/les-henokiens/|title=Les Hénokiens|publisher=[[Beretta]]|access-date=1 July 2015}}</ref> and now counts 47.<ref name="members">{{cite web|url=http://www.henokiens.com/content.php?id=5&lg=en|title=The Members|publisher=The Henokiens|access-date=1 July 2015}}</ref> Its stated objective and ''raison d'être'' is to promote long-term decision making, notably through its Da Vinci Prize.<ref>{{cite news |last= Bain |first= David|title= Henokiens: the world's most exclusive club|url= http://www.henokiens.com/userfiles/file/press/family-capital2015.pdf|newspaper= Family Capital|location= |date= 28 January 2015|access-date= 1 July 2015 }}</ref>
Its oldest member is the [[Japan]]ese [[Hōshi Ryokan|Hōshi]] [[ryokan (inn)|ryokan]] (founded 717), and the most recent the [[Austria]]n [[jewellery]] firm [[A. E. Köchert]] (founded 1814).
==Members== The association includes forty-four members. Marie Brizard, having been bought by an investment fund in 2000, is not a member anymore.
